<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n25179c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n25" href="#n25179c">N25 (VI.B.15)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n25all.htm#n25179c"> 179(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> sun moon birds / stela star ducks / fire &amp; water / = snake / thief = wind / cloudcows</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The terror of darkness caused him to regard all evil beings as belonging to the dark, and all good beings as belonging to light, and to life-giving warmth, as contrasted with the cold of death. Everything that moved, man regarded as being alive. The <mark>fire and the stream were living snakes</mark>; the <mark>sun and moon were great birds</mark>, and the little <mark>stars were their children</mark>. The storm was a warrior armed with thunderbolts. <mark>The breeze</mark> was an invisible swift messenger who was felt to pass by, or <mark>a clever thief</mark> who stole light things, or the faithful dog who drove the <mark>cloud-cows</mark> from the den of the detaining monster. <small> Claude R. Conder, <a name="CRRM" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#CRRM"><cite title="source">The Rise of Man</cite></a> (1908) 150-1</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c14120g" href="c14all.htm#c14120g">VI.C.14:120(g)</a>, <a name="c14120h" href="c14all.htm#c14120h">VI.C.14:120(h)</a>, <a name="c14120i" href="c14all.htm#c14120i">VI.C.14:120(i)</a>, <a name="c14120j" href="c14all.htm#c14120j">VI.C.14:120(j)</a>, <a name="c14120k" href="c14all.htm#c14120k">VI.C.14:120(k)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
